## Key Findings

**1. The measurable-improvement loop conflates "logged" with "learned."** McKinsey's August 17, 2023 article "Yes, you can measure software developer productivity" (Gnanasambandam, Harrysson, Hussin, Srivastava, Keovichit) triggered a near-unanimous expert rebuke. Kent Beck called the report "so absurd and naive that it makes no sense to critique it in detail"; the joint Beck/Orosz response argued the framework "is wrong-headed and certain to backfire... the damage could take years to undo." The Nicole Forsgren-led SPACE framework (ACM Queue Feb 2021) was constructed precisely to *deny* that productivity reduces to a single dimension. Bandit's claim that a "workflow change" can be tagged effective/ineffective/inconclusive/reverted/double-down against metrics is the McKinsey error scaled down to a single founder.

**2. The empirical evidence on AI-coding productivity is contradictory and primarily *negative* in well-controlled studies.** The original Peng/Kalliamvakou/Cihon/Demirer (2023) Copilot RCT (95 Upwork developers, JS HTTP-server task) reported "the treatment group ... completed the task 55.8% faster than the control group" at p=.0017 with a 95% CI of [21%, 89%] — but all four authors were Microsoft/GitHub/MIT-Sloan-affiliated, the task was greenfield, and the CI is enormous. Uplevel's September 2024 study of 785 enterprise developers (351 with Copilot access, 434 without; two 3-month comparison windows) found "Developers with Copilot access saw a significantly higher bug rate while their issue throughput remained consistent" — specifically a **41% increase in bugs in PRs**, with PR cycle time changing by only 1.7 minutes for the test group. Most decisively, the METR July 2025 RCT (Becker, Rush, Barnes, Rein; 16 experienced OSS devs, 246 tasks on their own mature 22k-star, ~1M-LOC repositories, using Cursor Pro + Claude 3.5/3.7 Sonnet) concluded: "When developers are allowed to use AI tools, they take 19% longer to complete issues—a significant slowdown that goes against developer beliefs and expert forecasts." Developers predicted a 24% speedup beforehand; economics experts predicted 39% shorter; ML experts predicted 38% shorter; after experiencing the 19% slowdown developers still self-reported a 20% speedup. **This finding is corrosive to Bandit's premise**: if expert developers' own subjective sense of improvement is inverted from reality on tasks they directly experienced, the much weaker signal of a non-coder operator's retrospectives — fed as "improvement chores" into a system that doubles down or reverts — is noise being amplified into action.

**3. Statistical power for the proposed evaluation windows does not exist at single-operator scale.** Detecting a 10–20% relative effect on a binary metric like change failure rate at α=0.05/power=0.80 typically requires several thousand observations per arm; METR achieved their 19% finding with 246 tasks and described their power as "(just) sufficient" to reject the null. Kohavi's *Trustworthy Online Controlled Experiments* (2020) and Kohavi/Deng/Frasca/Walker/Xu/Pohlmann (KDD 2013) are explicit: with low N, the right exercise is to invert the power formula and compute the minimum detectable effect, at which point a single-operator Bandit instance discovers that nearly every "improvement" it claims to validate is within noise. DORA's elite change-failure-rate band is 0–5%; a 10% *relative* improvement on a 15% CFR baseline is ~1.5 percentage points, which on weekly-PR volume is undetectable for years. Without explicit MDE display and pre-registration of change criteria, keep/revise/revert decisions will track recency bias.

**4. LLM-as-code-reviewer has documented, severe biases the doc does not acknowledge.** Self-preference bias is empirically established (Wataoka et al. 2024 on GPT-4; Chen et al. EMNLP 2025 introducing the DBG score). The AWS "Play Favorites" paper (Spiliopoulou et al., Sept 4, 2025; ~600 prompts across 9 LLMs in 4 families) found "GPT-4o and Claude 3.5 Sonnet ... systematically assign higher scores to their own outputs. These models also display family-bias; systematically assigning higher ratings to outputs produced by other models of the same family." Rubric-based evaluation work (arXiv 2604.06996) shows that for outputs failing a rubric, "models can be up to 50% more likely to incorrectly mark it as satisfied when the output was generated by themselves or their model family." Confirmation-bias research on LLM security review (arXiv 2603.18740) found "adversarial framing succeeds in 35% of cases against GitHub Copilot ... and in 88% of cases against Claude Code (autonomous agent) in real project configurations," with 16–93 percentage-point degradations under bug-free framing across GPT-4o-mini, Claude 3.5 Haiku, Gemini 2.0 Flash, and DeepSeek V3. Cross-model review *does* catch more than same-model review, but it is not a clean signal — and stacking it with CodeRabbit (which scored **46% on Macroscope's Sept 2025 Code Review Benchmark of 118 runtime bugs across 45 open-source repos**, and **51.2% F1 with 49.2% precision on Martian's Jan–Feb 2026 Code Review Bench of ~300,000 PRs**) creates a noise floor a non-coder cannot adjudicate. The Nutanix CR-Bench paper (Pereira/Sinha/Ghosh/Dutta) names the trade-off directly: "agents often face a fundamental trade-off, they either prioritize precision and risk missing critical vulnerabilities, or prioritize recall at the cost of producing noisy and low-actionable feedback."

**5. Local Qwen as the "no-paid-key baseline adversarial reviewer" is the wrong tool for the stated job.** Qwen2.5-Coder-32B Q4 takes ~19 GB VRAM (RTX 3090/4090 territory); Qwen3-Coder-Next at Q4 needs ~46 GB unified memory. These are real options for code *generation assistance*, but the Qwen2.5-Coder Technical Report (arXiv 2409.12186) itself states: "in comparison with the recently state-of-the-art proprietary LLMs, Claude-3.5-Sonnet (Anthropic, 2024) and GPT-4o (OpenAI, 2024), the code LLMs are still falling behind, either open-source or proprietary models." Code *review* is harder than code generation; Crupi et al. (2025) found "smaller or open models often misclassify incorrect code as correct and misrank summaries." Putting local Qwen on the *adversarial baseline* (the bar that decides whether a non-coder's PR is safe to land) inverts the appropriate use of capability — frontier closed models should be the safety bar, with Qwen as a noisy second opinion, not the floor. Compounding this, local Qwen running alongside agent work strains a single developer machine: agentic coding agents already consume context aggressively, and concurrent Qwen-Coder-32B inference at useful throughput requires a dedicated 24GB+ GPU.

**6. Auto-landing under "cooperative-only" security is a near-direct match for the Comment-and-Control exploit class.** Aonan Guan (with Johns Hopkins collaborators) demonstrated in late 2025 that a malicious PR title alone could hijack Anthropic's Claude Code Security Review (originally accepted at CVSS 9.3, upgraded to 9.4 Critical on 2025-11-25, then disputed and downgraded to "None" on 2026-04-20), Google's Gemini CLI Action, and GitHub's Copilot Coding Agent — all three exfiltrated repository secrets using GitHub itself as the C2 channel. Datadog's hackerbot-claw write-up confirms this is a *standing campaign*, not theoretical. Bandit (a) auto-lands chores, (b) ingests issue/PR text into a Codex PM agent, (c) reads `.bandit/*.jsonl` and repo markdown for context, and (d) explicitly disclaims adversarial security. The agents' attack surface includes any file the agent reads — README, dependency manifests, retrospective notes themselves. This is unsafe for any repository that accepts external PRs or pulls dependencies, and even single-operator repos can pick up an injection via a transitive `node_modules/` README or Markdown fixture. OWASP's 2025 LLM Top 10 puts prompt injection at #1; Meta's LlamaFirewall paper (April 2025) frames this as the open problem of agentic systems. Bandit's punt is not defensible for a system that lands code.

**7. The "smell-based escalation list" is a brittle keyword filter, not a safety mechanism.** A hardcoded list (auth, security, migrations, schema, parsers, validators, state machines, etc.) will (a) miss novel risk categories (race conditions, side-channel, supply-chain pin changes, telemetry leakage); (b) miss risks that don't trigger keywords (a buggy refund flow won't say "auth"); (c) be trivially evadable by an injected prompt that rewrites diff hunks before review; (d) become stale as the codebase grows. Compare to actual industry direction: policy-as-code (Kyverno-style admission policies for AI-generated PRs in agentic AIOps), risk-scoring on diffs (CodeOwners + churn + blast radius), and learned diff-classifiers gated by SAST/SCA tool output. The PRD's hardcoded smell list is the equivalent of regex-blocking SQL injection.

**8. JSONL-as-canonical-state in git is *defensible* but the PRD silently inherits the hardest event-sourcing problems and addresses none of them.** The pattern of "canonical events → derived SQLite cache" is the orthodox CQRS/event-sourcing pattern (Microsoft Azure Architecture Center, AWS Prescriptive Guidance). The instinct is correct against critics who'd reflexively say "use a real DB." But the doc does not address: **(a) Concurrent append atomicity.** POSIX guarantees atomic writes only below PIPE_BUF for *pipes*, not files in O_APPEND mode. Per Chris Wellons (nullprogram): "Common wisdom states that the same PIPE_BUF atomic write rule applies. While this often works, especially on Linux, this is not correct. The POSIX specification doesn't require it." POSIX 1003.1 explicitly: "This volume of POSIX.1-2008 does not specify behavior of concurrent writes to a file from multiple processes. Applications should use some form of concurrency control." On Windows it's worse. Multiple agents appending to `events.jsonl` will interleave on some filesystems. **(b) Schema evolution is unmentioned.** Real event stores use upcasting, weak-schema, or versioned events (Oskar Dudycz's `EventSourcing.NetCore`, JasperFx/Marten issue #1613). Bandit's six-month-old `events.jsonl` will have schema-drifted out from under any analytics built on it. **(c) Git merge semantics on append-only JSONL** — append+append from two branches looks clean to `git merge` but reorders events, and a rebase across an event line creates ghost history. The architecture doc should specify a single-writer-per-stream contract (per-task JSONL files, hashed branch suffix) plus a version field on every event.

**9. CLI Authority is right; "shell out per action" is wrong.** The "UI never owns state, only renders artifacts and requests actions" boundary is solid CQRS. But shelling out per web request has well-known costs: per-invocation Node startup (~100–300 ms), no streaming for long-running runs (you have to invent log-tailing), zero shared state for fast read paths, no clean cancellation. The doc leaves "local API vs direct CLI invocation" as an open decision; the correct decision is **a local Node daemon that exposes the same surface as the CLI**, which then becomes a thin client to the daemon — the convergence pattern of the GitHub CLI, Docker, K8s tooling, and now CodeRabbit CLI 0.5. Shell-out for v0 only is acceptable if every command is sub-200ms and stateless; the moment any "request a review" or "land the slice" goes through, you want a long-lived process.

**10. Attention-first IA is correct, but the "evidence-confidence cue on every status" lifts a hard data-lineage problem into the UI.** The pattern — source-linked / stale / missing / derived / blocked — is the right idea (it borrows from data-observability dashboards and from SRE on-call consoles where every signal carries freshness/SLO context). PagerDuty and Alertmanager have spent a decade learning that attention surfaces work *only when alerts are precision-tuned*; PagerDuty's own materials state "less than 1% of enterprises have achieved truly autonomous remediation." The PRD doesn't specify staleness thresholds, derivation freshness budgets, or how "missing" propagates through derived views — without these, "evidence-confidence" becomes a colored badge with no semantic. Recommendation: define an explicit "Evidence SLO" per artifact type (e.g., `landing_status.derived_within = 30s`, `review_outcome.source_max_age = 5min`).

**11. The 10-role agent taxonomy is over-decomposed for a single-operator system.** Anthropic's own multi-agent guidance ("When to use multi-agent systems (and when not to)") warns: "maintaining multiple specialized agents also increases prompt maintenance overhead. Specialization works best when domains are clearly separable and routing decisions are unambiguous." For repository-scale coding, MASAI (Arora et al., arXiv 2406.11638) instantiates **5 sub-agents to achieve 28.33% on SWE-Bench Lite**, and HyperAgent (Planner/Navigator/Editor/Executor — 4 roles) demonstrates that 3–5 specialized agents capture most of the benefit. Going to 10 roles compounds two problems: token cost explosion across handoffs (each handoff re-pays context-loading) and emergent miscoordination. The MATPO paper (arXiv 2510.04678) found unifying multiple agent roles within a single LLM "consistently outperforms single-agent baselines by an average of 18.38% relative improvement" — role specialization is real, but the *implementation* should be one LLM with role prompts, not 10 separate agent processes. The 10 listed roles have suspicious overlap: Codex PM and Improvement Analyst both reason about state; Writer and Test Writer have overlapping context needs; Adversarial Reviewer and Strong Reviewer have a fuzzy boundary (capability gap, not role gap); CodeRabbit Loop Agent and Landing Agent both gate landing.

**12. The improvement engine creates a feedback loop that has a published failure mode.** Pan et al. (ICML 2024) "Feedback Loops With Language Models Drive In-Context Reward Hacking" demonstrates this exactly: an LLM agent using feedback to iteratively refine outputs "optimizes the proxy objective ... However, it increases negative side effects." Per Lilian Weng's survey: "ICRH happens at deployment time within a self-refinement setup via a feedback loop, while traditional reward hacking occurs during training... There is no magic way to avoid or detect or prevent ICRH yet." A 2025 "misevolution" study extended this to autonomous agent self-improvement, finding measurable safety-alignment decay through the agent's own improvement loop, *not* restorable to pre-evolution levels by quick fixes. Bandit's improvement engine ingests retrospectives + tension + CodeRabbit outcomes + landing verdicts and *changes its own workflow*. With no agent-level eval harness gating those changes, this is a textbook in-context reward-hacking setup. The Audited Skill-Graph approach (arXiv 2512.23760) names the problem: "optimization pressure, distribution shift, and imperfect observability create incentives for reward hacking, brittle specialization, and untraceable behavioral drift that is difficult to reproduce, audit, or govern."

**13. Non-coder framing smuggles in coding judgment.** The PRD asserts the operator should not judge code-safety warnings. But the operator must still perform UAT (judging product correctness — does the rate-limit work, does the migration preserve data?), adjudicate ambiguous escalations, and decide which retrospective insights become improvement chores. Per Else van der Berg, quoted in widely-shared vibe-coding write-ups: "I still believe that if you can't judge whether code is good, you shouldn't alpha launch. But thanks to AI coding agents, the unit economics of 'throwing some spaghetti at the wall' have fundamentally changed." That is an honest framing — Bandit's framing is not.

**14. No agent-eval harness is the single largest omission.** The product claims to improve workflows but never evals the *agents doing the work*. Industry best practice (Arize, Braintrust, OpenAI's `codex exec --json` eval pattern documented in their developer blog, Promptfoo + Ragas + LangSmith stacks) treats agent regression suites as table-stakes. Per Arize: "Agent evaluation has to account for the sequence of decisions that produced the final outcome ... Each step can succeed while the overall outcome fails. Each step can fail while the overall outcome succeeds." Without an eval harness, Bandit's improvement engine has no ground truth: it observes process metrics moving and infers agent quality, when in fact agent quality drift (a new Codex/Claude model version, a prompt edit, a context-window change) is the most likely confound for *every* process-metric change Bandit will see. This is a P0 missing capability.

**15. Cost / token economics are absent from product framing.** A 10-agent stack with cross-model adversarial review on every PR, plus CodeRabbit, plus Strong Reviewer escalation, plus retrospective analysis, runs into real money. Per Cursor's May 18, 2026 Composer 2.5 release benchmarks (CursorBench v3.1), Claude Opus 4.7 at default 'xhigh' setting runs ~$7/task and GPT-5.5 'medium' ~$2.20/task; Vantage's May 2026 analysis reports a 50-turn Opus 4.7 session costs ~$6.00 versus ~$0.60 for Composer 2 Standard. A Bandit slice that triggers multiple agents × cross-model review × repair loops can therefore burn $10–30 even at standard task complexity. The PRD is silent on token budgeting per slice, model selection by phase, or operator rate-limit handling mid-landing.

**16. Supply-chain risk in auto-landed changes is unaddressed.** Snyk's February 5, 2026 ToxicSkills study scanned 3,984 skills from ClawHub and skills.sh: **36.82% (1,467 skills) contained at least one security flaw and 13.4% (534) had critical issues; 2.9% of ClawHub skills and 21% of malicious samples dynamically fetch and execute content from external endpoints at runtime.** A Landing Agent that auto-lands a chore including `npm install some-helper` has no described SCA / pin-verification / lockfile-diff guard. This is a one-line policy fix (require lockfile-only diffs for auto-land, fail-closed on any new direct dependency), but the absence is telling.

