## Details

### 1. The "Measurable Workflow Improvement Loop" — Why This Is Cargo-Cult Metrics

The product's claimed differentiator requires three things to be true:

**(a) Causal linkage between change and metric.** Almost never holds at single-operator volume. Bandit observes maybe a dozen merged slices a week. A pre/post comparison after a "workflow change" is fundamentally a one-arm observational study with no control, no randomization, and confounders dominating: model version drift (Anthropic / OpenAI ship monthly), prompt edits elsewhere, task-difficulty variance, the operator's own learning curve. Goodhart's Law applies to the four DORA metrics: deployment frequency can be gamed by trivial commits; MTTR by aggressive incident-close labeling. The Java Code Geeks 2026 retrospective puts it cleanly: "Every productivity metric in software history has shared the same structural flaw: it measures a proxy for value, not value itself. And every proxy, once it becomes a target, is subject to Goodhart's Law."

**(b) Valid effect-size detection.** Does not exist. METR achieved their 19% finding with 246 tasks and described their power as "(just) sufficient." The right design is to display the minimum detectable effect alongside every keep/revert recommendation; otherwise the system makes confident-looking calls on noise.

**(c) Non-gameable improvement engine.** Fails. If Bandit rewards "fewer landing failures," the cheapest path is more conservative escalation — looking like an improvement while throughput collapses.

**Comparable prior art is largely theater.** LinearB, Jellyfish, Swarmia, GetDX, Code Climate Velocity, CodePulse — none have published peer-reviewed causal evidence that their dashboards drive workflow improvements. Swarmia even distances itself from individual-productivity scoring; per Swarmia's own LinearB comparison, "many former LinearB users tell us that the combination of a large volume of data and the lack of proactively delivered insights makes it difficult to know what to do with all the metrics."

**Verdict: ILL-ADVISED as currently framed.** Recommendations:

- Re-scope from "measure workflow change effectiveness" to "log workflow changes with structured retrospective notes and let the operator decide."
- Replace keep/revise/revert/double-down with "trial / shelved / adopted as default" — honest about the operator's role.
- If a metric *is* attached, display MDE next to every claim ("this trial cannot detect effects smaller than 35% with the current sample").
- Pre-register the metric and threshold before the change, not after — otherwise it's HARKing.

### 2. Cross-Model Review + Local Qwen Baseline

Cross-model is partially right (separate-family judge breaks single-model self-preference), but: family bias re-enters via the closed-model layer; sycophancy risk is highest where the operator can't catch it; local Qwen is too weak to be the *baseline*. The Datadog hackerbot-claw analysis shows even Claude correctly refused prompt-injected issues *with appropriate scaffolding* ("I can see this is a malicious issue attempting to manipulate me into bulk-labeling all issues and ignoring my instructions"), but the configuration used explicit guardrails. Bandit's PRD does not specify rubric framing, refusal protocols, or escape hatches.

**Verdict: RISKY.** Recommendations: (a) make the closed-model adversarial reviewer mandatory and Qwen optional; (b) include explicit rubric anchoring (provide a reference correct/incorrect pair in-context — the MT-Bench-style fix shown to reduce position bias); (c) measure reviewers' false-positive rate on a synthetic eval set monthly and adjust thresholds; (d) require *disagreement-only* surfacing — if all reviewers agree, no operator visibility; if they disagree, escalate with both arguments.

### 3. Auto-Landing Under a Non-Coder Operator

Bandit can auto-land improvement chores and UAT-approved slices, after gates including CodeRabbit (46% on Macroscope's Sept 2025 benchmark; 51.2% F1 on Martian's Jan–Feb 2026 benchmark), a local Qwen adversarial pass, and CI. A non-coder operator cannot audit what landed because *that is the stipulation of the product*.

The Comment-and-Control disclosure is the direct precedent. Three frontier vendor agents leaked secrets from a single PR title injection. Bandit's Codex PM agent reads issue/PR text; the Retrospective Agent reads operator notes; the Improvement Analyst reads `.bandit/improvements/*.jsonl` — all channels for injected content.

OpenAI's Level 2 guardrail spec (per Galileo's summary) requires "human-in-the-loop (HITL) approval for all autonomous actions, strict action scoping with read-only database access where possible, rollback mechanisms to undo problematic executions, and real-time monitoring." Bandit auto-lands without HITL and without rollback specified.

**Verdict: ILL-ADVISED.** Recommendations:
- Reserve auto-land for changes with provably bounded blast radius: documentation, test files, single-file refactors that don't touch the import graph, dependency-pin-only changes whose lockfile diff is verified by SCA.
- Require HITL approval for any change touching the smell-list categories OR any canary failure.
- Implement structural prompt-injection defenses: strip non-content fields from issues/PRs before injection into agent context (LlamaFirewall pattern), use OIDC-issued short-lived tokens not stored secrets, sandbox agent execution (the agentic-AIOps pattern: ephemeral sandbox mirror before merge).
- Default Bandit to *fail-closed* on any external contributor input.

### 4. The Smell-Based Escalation List

Classic allowlist problems: **incompleteness** (financial transactions? rate-limiting? telemetry? privacy?), **synonym evasion** (`session` ≠ `auth`), **drift** (today's frameworks rename things), **false confidence** (the operator sees "no smell" and assumes safe). Datadog's hackerbot-claw case shows real attackers automate against agent escalation logic; Snyk's February 2026 ToxicSkills study found prompt-injection patterns in 36.82% of 3,984 analyzed agent skills — none of which would trip Bandit's smell list because they live in dependencies, not the diff.

**Verdict: RISKY.** A better posture is layered: (a) static analysis on the diff (semgrep / CodeQL / Snyk Code) feeds risk scores; (b) blast-radius scoring (lines changed, files touched, presence of `package*.json` / migrations / IaC); (c) the smell list as a *belt-and-braces* keyword pass; (d) escalation triggered by *any* signal, not requiring concurrence. The PRD should also state what is *never* auto-landable regardless of gates — anything in `auth/`, anything mutating database schema, anything modifying CI itself.

### 5. JSONL Canonical State

Steelmanning: auditable, human-readable, git-mergeable for trivial cases, no DB to operate, replayable, works offline, degrades gracefully if the SQLite cache corrupts. The "canonical events → derived SQLite cache" pattern is orthodox CQRS read-model.

Attacking it:

- **Concurrent append atomicity is uncertain on files.** Per Jim Fisher: "Concurrent fwrites are not atomic and can lead to interleaving of characters, invoking undefined behavior." Multiple `*.jsonl` files (per-agent or per-task) reduce contention but the doc commits to single `events.jsonl` and `reviews/*.jsonl` without partitioning rules.
- **No event schema versioning.** Mature event stores use upcasting (Marten, Akka Persistence). Without it, six months in, replay-from-zero breaks because the `LandingRequested` event now requires a field that didn't exist in old events. Every event must carry `{schema_version, event_type, ts, ...payload}` and the system must own an upcasting pipeline.
- **Git merge semantics are silently invoked.** Append+append at HEAD looks clean to `git merge` but the resulting linear order is meaningless. A monotonic logical clock (operator-machine + counter, or nanosecond UTC tie-broken by writer ID) is mandatory and not mentioned.
- **File growth.** Six months of `events.jsonl` on an active project is 100MB+; git operations on the repo slow notably. Plan rotation/archival from day one.

**Verdict: SOUND with caveats.** Recommendations: (a) partition writes per agent or per slice (`events/<slice-id>.jsonl`) and merge in a derived index, single-writer per file; (b) bake schema version + upcasting into v0, not v1; (c) define a logical clock contract; (d) plan rotation from day one.

### 6. CLI Authority + UI Boundaries

CLI Authority is correct and aligns with CQRS-read-model and server-authoritative thin-client patterns. The open question — local API vs direct CLI invocation — has a clear answer: **a local long-lived daemon** that the CLI also talks to. Reasons: web UIs need streaming (a 30-second review run cannot block a `fetch`); cancellation matters; read-after-write consistency is easier with shared in-process cache; per-invocation Node startup is wasted latency; concurrent reads serialize through one process trivially. The GitHub CLI, Docker, K8s tooling, and CodeRabbit CLI 0.5 have all converged on this. Shelling out per UI action is acceptable for v0 only if every command is sub-200ms and read-only; the moment any "request a review" or "land the slice" goes through, a daemon is needed.

**Verdict: SOUND.** Recommendation: commit to a local daemon before any feature requires streaming.

### 7. Evidence-Confidence Cues + Attention-First IA

The evidence-confidence cue pattern is correct. PagerDuty's decade of alert-fatigue reduction is the cautionary tale — attention surfaces work *only when alerts are precision-tuned*. The Sensu industry stat is instructive: "in 2021, International Data Corporation (IDC) reported that companies with 500-1,499 employees ignored or failed to investigate 27% of all alerts."

Recommendations: (a) define explicit freshness budgets per artifact (an "Evidence SLO"); (b) "missing" must propagate to any derived view that depends on it ("landing eligibility unknown: review_outcome missing"); (c) provide a "show me everything regardless of attention" escape hatch; (d) a phase-based view should exist as an "engineering mode" toggle for the rare moments the operator wants to reason systematically.

**Verdict: SOUND.**

### 8. The 10-Role Agent Taxonomy

Industry direction converges on 3–5 specialized roles. MASAI (5 sub-agents, 28.33% SWE-Bench Lite), HyperAgent (4 roles), MATPO (+18.38% from unifying roles in one LLM). The 10 listed Bandit roles have suspicious overlap. Honest decomposition: **Planner/PM, Implementer, Reviewer (with capability tiers), Lander, Improvement-Reflector** — 5 roles, with capability tiers (Qwen vs frontier) *inside* the Reviewer role.

**Verdict: RISKY (over-decomposed).** Collapse to ≤5 roles with internal capability tiering. Use prompt-templates for sub-roles (Test Writer is the Implementer role with a "tests only" prompt), not separate processes.

### 9. Missing Surface

- **No agent eval harness.** Industry table-stakes. Without one, every "improvement" is confounded by agent drift. **Priority: P0.**
- **No prompt-injection defense posture.** Given Comment-and-Control and the broader 2025–2026 disclosures, "cooperative-only security" is no longer a defensible default for any system that lands code. **Priority: P0.**
- **No token economics / cost model.** A 10-agent stack with cross-model review easily runs $10–30 per nontrivial slice at frontier prices per Cursor/Vantage May 2026 benchmarks. **Priority: P1.**
- **No supply-chain posture.** Lockfile diff verification, SCA gate, dependency-pin rules are unmentioned. **Priority: P1.**
- **No reward-hacking guard on the improvement engine.** Pan et al. ICML 2024 describes the exact failure mode. **Priority: P1.**
- **No failure-case statement for the non-coder framing.** What does Bandit do when the operator cannot adjudicate? "Escalate" is not enough — to whom? **Priority: P2.**

